Headline::::
Ask Alys: which flowers can I plant on a damp grave?




DateTime::::2016-02-20T06:00:41+0000



<p><strong>Can you suggest anything I can plant at my mother’s grave? The ground is exposed and waterlogged. </strong><br/>I can quite understand that you want her grave to look loved and cared for. You don’t say whether the ground is waterlogged all year round, but I am going to assume that it remains damp all year.</p>

<p>Cemeteries tend to have a lot of wildlife, which means plants do get munched. <em>Vinca minor</em>, the lesser periwinkle, will survive anywhere, though you may have to give it an annual trim in spring. It has lovely lavender-blue flowers and will flower from April through to September. And it won’t be nibbled, and will look after itself.</p>

<p> <span>Related: </span><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/gardening-blog/2016/feb/06/ask-alys-pond-blanket-weed">Ask Alys: our pond suffers from blanket weed. Help!</a> </p>

<p>If there aren’t too many rabbits or deer, you could also try primulas, such as the giant cowslip, <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/13757/i-Primula-florindae-i-(Si)/Details"><em>Primula florindae</em></a><em>, </em>which has scented, nodding sulphur yellow flowers. If it’s happy, it often self-seeds, and it’s tough enough to cope with being planted in grass, as long as you remove some of the grass around it so it can establish. There are a few other primulas<em> – </em><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/13785/i-Primula-japonica-i-(Pf)/Details"><em>P. japonica</em></a>, <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/90564/i-Primula-prolifera-i-(Pf)/Details">P. <em>prolifera</em></a> and<em> </em><a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="https://www.rhs.org.uk/Plants/13860/i-Primula-pulverulenta-i-(Pf)/Details"><em>P. pulverulenta</em></a> – that like damp conditions, but you may need to remove some of the grass in order for them to establish. And they won’t like to be in full sun all day long, unless the ground is very damp indeed.</p>

<p><span class="bullet">•</span> Got a question for Alys Fowler? Email <a class="u-underline" data-component="in-body-link" data-link-name="in body link" href="mailto:askalys@theguardian.com">askalys@theguardian.com</a></p>




